<doc id="508070" wikidata="Q2164293" url="?curid=508070" title="Telescoping series">
<text>In mathematics, a telescoping series is a series whose general term formula_1 is of the form formula_2, i.e. the difference of two consecutive terms of a sequence formula_3. As a consequence the partial sums of the series only consists of two terms of formula_3 after cancellation. 

The cancellation technique, with part of each term cancelling with part of the next term, is known as the method of differences.

An early statement of the formula for the sum or partial sums of a telescoping series can be found in a 1644 work by Evangelista Torricelli, &quot;De dimensione parabolae&quot;.

== Definition ==
Telescoping sums are finite sums in which pairs of consecutive terms partly cancel each other, leaving only parts of the initial and final terms. Let formula_5 be the elements of a sequence of numbers. Then
formula_6
If formula_7 converges to a limit formula_8, the telescoping series gives:
formula_9

Every series is a telescoping series of its own partial sums.

